10 Mental Traps That Quietly Control Your Thinking  Our brain is not a tool for truth, it is a tool for survival. It doesnâ€™t look for whatâ€™s right, it looks for whatâ€™s fast.  Every decision passes through hidden filters. They save energy but distort perception.  Thatâ€™s why smart people make stupid mistakes. Not because theyâ€™re stupid, but because theyâ€™re human.  Here are 10 traps we all fall into:  1. Confirmation Bias â†³ you only notice what confirms your beliefs.  2. Dunningâ€“Kruger Effect â†³ the less you know, the more confident you feel.  3. Sunk Cost Fallacy â†³ you keep going simply because youâ€™ve already invested.  4. Negativity Bias â†³ one bad event outweighs ten good ones.  5. Anchoring Bias â†³ the first number or idea distorts everything that follows.  6. Halo Effect â†³ charisma makes you believe in competence.  7. Authority Bias â†³ you trust confidence, not accuracy.  8. Availability Heuristic â†³ whatâ€™s easier to recall feels more true.  9. Groupthink â†³ you stay silent to fit in.  10. Survivorship Bias â†³ you study the winners and forget the ones who didnâ€™t make it.  Our brain was built to survive, not to understand. Awareness is the only way out of this game.  Below is the infographic with a deeper breakdown of each trap, with examples and simple ways to spot and neutralize them.  ğŸ’¬ Which of these traps do you fall for most often?  â€” @natan_mohart

ğŸš¨TUTORIAL ALERT!!!ğŸš¨ Comment "GEM" for the Project File Link.  Tutorial we all have been waiting for!!!!  Step-By-Step Guide on:  How to create a 3D Anime Crystal in Adobe After Effects?  Step 1- Create a crystal shape using the pen tool. Draw a mask over it, turn on the 3D switch, and add stroke effect on it.  Step 2- By rotating the shapes inwards, create a 3D crystal-like shape; the points of each shape should be connected. Make a similar crystal but with a fill in another comp.  Step 3- Duplicate both stroke and fill comps and link both of them to a Null object, and flip it to form a whole crystal.  Step 4- Add 2 point lights to give some depth and a crystal-like hue.  Step 5- Add roughen edges to the stroke comp and change the blending mode to overlay.  Step 6- Add a Deep glow to the crystal using an adjustment layer.   Step 7- Add Twinkly sparkles to the crystal to give it a shinier look.  The Anime Crystal Is Ready!!!!  Try creating by yourself! Don't forget to tag me!! ğŸš¨TUTORIAL ALERT!!!ğŸš¨ Comment "GEM" for the Project File Link.  Tutorial we all have been waiting for!!!!  Step-By-Step Guide on:  How to create a 3D Anime Crystal in Adobe After Effects?  Step 1- Create a crystal shape using the pen tool. Draw a mask over it, turn on the 3D switch, and add stroke effect on it.  Step 2- By rotating the shapes inwards, create a 3D crystal-like shape; the points of each shape should be connected. Make a similar crystal but with a fill in another comp.  Step 3- Duplicate both stroke and fill comps and link both of them to a Null object, and flip it to form a whole crystal.  Step 4- Add 2 point lights to give some depth and a crystal-like hue.  Step 5- Add roughen edges to the stroke comp and change the blending mode to overlay.  Step 6- Add a Deep glow to the crystal using an adjustment layer.   Step 7- Add Twinkly sparkles to the crystal to give it a shinier look.  The Anime Crystal Is Ready!!!!  Try creating by yourself! Don't forget to tag me!! 10 Mental Traps That Quietly Control Your Thinking  Our brain is not a tool for truth, it is a tool for survival. It doesnâ€™t look for whatâ€™s right, it looks for whatâ€™s fast.  Every decision passes through hidden filters. They save energy but distort perception.  Thatâ€™s why smart people make stupid mistakes. Not because theyâ€™re stupid, but because theyâ€™re human.  Here are 10 traps we all fall into:  1. Confirmation Bias â†³ you only notice what confirms your beliefs.  2. Dunningâ€“Kruger Effect â†³ the less you know, the more confident you feel.  3. Sunk Cost Fallacy â†³ you keep going simply because youâ€™ve already invested.  4. Negativity Bias â†³ one bad event outweighs ten good ones.  5. Anchoring Bias â†³ the first number or idea distorts everything that follows.  6. Halo Effect â†³ charisma makes you believe in competence.  7. Authority Bias â†³ you trust confidence, not accuracy.  8. Availability Heuristic â†³ whatâ€™s easier to recall feels more true.  9. Groupthink â†³ you stay silent to fit in.  10. Survivorship Bias â†³ you study the winners and forget the ones who didnâ€™t make it.  Our brain was built to survive, not to understand. Awareness is the only way out of this game.  Below is the infographic with a deeper breakdown of each trap, with examples and simple ways to spot and neutralize them.  ğŸ’¬ Which of these traps do you fall for most often?  â€” @natan_mohart

Hereâ€™s a quick rundown of how CAD has evolved over the decades:  ğŸ‘‰ 1940s-1950s: Started with basic numerical control systems and Dr. Hanrattyâ€™s PRONTO in 1957 - the real beginning of CAD  ğŸ‘‰ 1960s: Ivan Sutherland created SKETCHPAD (1963) with the first graphical interface, plus Pierre BÃ©zier developed UNISURF - all on huge mainframe computers  ğŸ‘‰ 1970s: Companies like Intergraph and IBM jumped in, and we started seeing the first 3D wireframe models instead of just 2D drawings  ğŸ‘‰ 1980s: Game changer! IBM PC arrived (1981), then Autodesk launched AutoCAD (1982) - suddenly CAD wasnâ€™t just for big companies anymore  ğŸ‘‰ 1990s: Personal computers got powerful enough for real 3D modeling. SolidWorks (1995) made 3D design accessible to everyone  ğŸ‘‰ 2000s-2010s: Cloud computing, better graphics, parametric modeling became standard, and CAD started talking to manufacturing machines  â¡ï¸ Today: Weâ€™ve got AI-assisted design, real-time collaboration, virtual reality integration, and CAD that connects everything from initial sketch to final product  #cad #evolution #ai #3dai
